&gt; I&#39;m curious how others in the community feel about this?

That&#39;s opinion-based and so off-topic for SO, so I&#39;ll answer according to whether the semicolon is *meant* to be there per the language specification (e.g., if you leave it off, are you relying on automatic semicolon insertion [ASI]?).

Yes, you use a semicolon after the arrow function, because the semi terminates the assignment statement. (In contrast, your first code block is a function **declaration**, not an expression, so no semicolon after it.) It&#39;s the same situation as with a traditional function expression:

    const add = function(a, b) {
      const sum = a + b;
      return sum;
    }; // &lt;== Note

Naturally, ASI applies as it does in JavaScript generally, so you&#39;ll *usually* be okay leaving it off and letting ASI supply it. (I prefer to be explicit and put them in.) I say *usually* because if the next line starts with a `(` or a `[` or a backtick, ASI won&#39;t add the semi for you, because it thinks that&#39;s still part of the expression. (That&#39;s why people who rely on ASI put a `;` at the beginning of lines that would otherwise start with one of those characters.)

For what it&#39;s worth, [my answer discussing the various forms of functions in JavaScript](https://stackoverflow.com/a/22173438/157247) has all required semicolons *(I hope!)*, and no extra ones *(I hope!)*, so if you want examples...

