Traditional Javascript functions look like this:
```
function add(a, b) {
  var sum = a + b;
  return sum;
}
```
With ES6, we now have fat-arrow functions.  I&#39;ve been writing them like this:
```
const add = (a, b) =&gt; {
  const sum = a + b;
  return sum;
}
```
Note that in both examples, I did not use a trailing semicolon after the final curly brace.  A colleague, who comes from a Java background, feels it&#39;s fine to not have a trailing semi-colon with a `function` but insists that there should be one with a `const` fat-arrow function.  I&#39;ve cited this article, supporting  the contrary: https://medium.com/@thakkery/a-practical-style-guide-to-semi-colons-in-es6-c4f63d03a904

I&#39;m curious how others in the community feel about this?

